         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>
               <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/> lords <supplied reason="lost">of the earth</supplied> under the sun <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/> fortunate, Augusti <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
               <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">gave</supplied> to the city to further its prosperity <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/> of themselves  <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
               <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">by action of</supplied> the distinguished <supplied reason="lost">governor</supplied>
            </p></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The style recalls <ref type="inscription">P13900</ref> of the
                    joint reign of Arcadius and Honorius (395-408) to whom perhaps this text also
                    refers.</p>
            <p>l.1: For the formula cf. e.g. <title>Aphrodisias in Late Antiquity</title> (2004), 25, 26, 27 <!--xref--></p>
            <p>The emperors had apparently made some gift to the city; and it may be that this
                    should be connected with the embassy of Synesius to Constantinople to ask
                    Arcadius for imperial aid for the province, cf. <foreign xml:lang="grc">περὶ βασιλείας</foreign> 1100 c for a
                    reference to restoration of buildings. 
                    <!--<xref>Should we have an n xref to the translation, http://www.livius.org/su-sz/synesius/synesius_monarchy_17.html</xref>--></p>
            <p>l.5: The title of the imperial agent, probably the praeses, who carried out the work or dedicated it.</p>
         </div>
         
